Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Eynon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>Enniaun</i>, an old Welsh personal name ultimately derived from Late Latin <i>Annianus</i>, but also associated with Welsh <i>einion</i> ‘anvil’, taken as implying stability and fortitude. See also   Beynon   and compare   Onion  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Beynon","meanings":["Welsh (southern): variant of   Bennion  ."]},{"name":"Hennion","meanings":["Welsh: from a hypercorrected form of the Welsh personal name <i>Ennion</i>, see   Eynon  .","Flemish and French (mainly Nord): from a pet form of the personal name   Henri   or <i>Jehen</i> (see   Jean  )."]},{"name":"Bennion","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Einion</i>, <i>ap Eynon</i> ‘son of <i>Einion</i>’ (see   Eynon  )."]},{"name":"Binion","meanings":["Traditional: originally a byname meaning ‘anvil’."]},{"name":"Kenyon","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin a local name from any of various places so called. The one in Devon gets its name from the British river name <i>Kenn</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’ the one in north-west London is from the Old English personal name <i>Cēna</i> + <i>tūn</i>; the one in Northumberland is from Old English <i>cyne-</i> ‘royal’ + <i>tūn</i>."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":28,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Eynon Baynham was born in 1354, in Mitchelde